{{Infobox book | name = The 4-Hour Workweek: Escape 9-5, Live Anywhere, and Join the New Rich | title_orig = | translator = | image = The 4-Hour Workweek (front cover).jpg | caption = | author = [[Timothy Ferriss|Tim Ferriss]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = Barbara Sturman | country = United States | language = English | series = | subject = [[Self-actualization]], [[Self-employment]], [[Self-improvement]] | genre = Non-fiction | published = 2007 ([[Crown Publishing Group]]) | media_type =Tv/Literature | pages = 308 pp | isbn = 978-0-307-35313-9 | dewey= 650.1 22 | congress= HD6955 .F435 2007 | oclc= 76262350 | preceded_by = | followed_by = [[The 4-Hour Body]] }}
'''''The 4-Hour Workweek: Escape 9-5, Live Anywhere, and Join the New Rich''''' (2007) is a [[self-help]] book by [[Timothy Ferriss]], an American writer, educational activist, and [[entrepreneur]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Ferriss |first=Timothy |title=The 4-Hour Workweek: Escape 9-5, Live Anywhere, and Join the New Rich |publisher=Crown Publishing Group |year=2007 |isbn=978-0-307-35313-9 }}</ref> The book has spent more than four years on [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Best Seller List]], has been translated into 35 languages and has sold more than 1,350,000 copies worldwide.<ref name="publishersmarketplace">[http://www.publishersmarketplace.com/members/swhanselma/ Best-Known Projects]. ''Publishers Marketplace''.</ref><ref name="newyorktimesbestsellerlist">[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/01/books/bestseller/hardcover-business-best-sellers.html Hardcover Business Best Sellers]. ''The New York Times''. May 1, 2011.</ref><ref name="fourhourworkweekblog">[http://www.fourhourworkweek.com/blog/about/ Bio]. ''FourHourWorkWeek.com/Blog''.</ref> It deals with what Ferriss refers to as "lifestyle design" and repudiates the traditional "deferred" life plan in which people work grueling hours and take few vacations for decades and save money in order to relax after [[retirement]].
==Background== Ferriss developed the ideas present in ''The 4-Hour Workweek'' (4HWW) while working 14-hour days at his [[sports nutrition]] supplement company, BrainQUICKEN.<ref name=abcnews>Maney, Kevin; Chapula, Andrea. [http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/story?id=3753402&page=1#.UCUrG0SIqOU Tim Ferriss Wants You to Get A Life]. ''ABC News''. October 11, 2007.</ref> Frustrated by the overwork and lack of free time, Ferriss took a 3-week sabbatical to [[Europe]]. During that time and continued travels throughout Europe, Asia, and South America, Ferriss developed a streamlined system of checking [[email]] once per day and [[outsourcing]] small daily tasks to [[Virtual assistant (occupation)|virtual assistant]]s.<ref name=newyorktimes>Rosenbloom, Stephanie. [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/27/fashion/27Ferris.html?_r=1&pagewanted=1 The World According to Tim Ferriss]. ''The New York Times''. March 25, 2011.</ref> His personal escape from a [[workaholic]] lifestyle was the genesis of the book.<ref name=fastcompany>Ohannessian, Kevin. [http://www.fastcompany.com/1718921/leadership-hall-fame-tim-ferriss-author-4-hour-workweek Leadership Hall of Fame: Tim Ferriss, Author of "The 4-Hour Workweek"]. ''Fast Company''. January 20, 2011.</ref>
The format of ''The 4-Hour Workweek'' took shape during a series of lectures Ferriss delivered on high-tech entrepreneurship at [[Princeton University]], his [[alma mater]].<ref name=thedailyprincetonian>Hall, Cornelia. [http://www.dailyprincetonian.com/2007/05/09/18434/ Ferriss '00 takes the day off]. ''The Daily Princetonian''. May 9, 2007.</ref> The lectures (and book) described Ferriss' own experiences in company automation and lifestyle development.<ref name=thedailyprincetonian/>
